## Statistical Analysis 
 All analyses were conducted in R (version: 4.5.1). Descriptive statistics were reported as frequencies and percentages for all categorical variables. The prevalence of Internet Gaming Disorder (IGD) was estimated using the IGD-20 instrument [CITATION], with a 95% Wilson confidence interval calculated to account for the binary outcome. Internal consistency of each IGD-20 subscale was assessed using Cronbach's α, with values ≥ 0.70 considered acceptable.
  Grade Point Average (GPA) was treated as an ordinal outcome with four levels (<2.5, 2.5–3.74, 3.75–4.49, 4.5–5.0) and analyzed using cumulative link models (CLM) with a logit link function, implemented via the ordinal package in R. Unadjusted odds ratios (ORs) were estimated through univariable CLM for each predictor. Two multivariable CLMs were subsequently constructed. Model selection was based on a likelihood ratio test (LRT) comparing nested models, alongside the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) and Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), with lower values indicating better fit. Results were considered statistically significant at a two-sided p-value < 0.05.
