## Participant Characteristics
A total of 485 university students were included in the final analysis after excluding incomplete responses. The majority were aged between 20 and 23 years (n = 293, 60.4%), single (n = 444, 91.5%), and living with their family (n = 455, 93.8%). Students were distributed across six health sciences colleges, with Applied Medical Sciences representing the largest proportion (n = 170, 35.1%). Fifty participants (10.3%) reported a history of psychiatric diagnosis, and 57 (11.8%) were current smokers (Table 1). With respect to academic performance, 6 (1.2%), 104 (21.4%), 227 (46.8%), and 148 (30.5%) students fell within the GPA categories of <2.5, 2.5–3.74, 3.75–4.49, and 4.5–5.0, respectively.



